gland":"Yorkshire West Riding, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Totty","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Tot(t)i</i>, a variant of <i>Tot(t)e</i>, representing either Old English <i>Tot(t)a</i> (of uncertain origin) or Old Scandinavian <i>Tóti</i>, which is probably a pet form of Old Scandinavian <i>Thorsteinn</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>toti</i> ‘dizzy, unsteady, befuddled’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Totty was born in 1349, in Rolleston, Staffordshire, England, her father, Thomas Totty, was 25 and her mother, Eleanor, was 19. She married Robert Leventhorpe in 1369, in Yorkshire West Riding, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died after 1377, in Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"1349–after 1377":"1349–pärast 1377","1349–1377":"1349–1377","1345–1377":"1345–1377","1370–1433":"1370–1433","1371–1422":"1371–1422","1375–1433":"1375–1433","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1330":"1330","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","1349":"1349","1369":"1369","1324":"1324","1378":"1378","1422":"1422","1433":"1433","1345":"1345","1377":"1377","1375":"1375","after 1377":"pärast 1377","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Bradford, Yorkshire, England":"Bradford, Yorkshire, England","Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, England":"Sawbridgeworth, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rolleston, Staffordshire, England":"Rolleston, Staffordshire, England","West Riding, Yorkshire, England, UK":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yorkshire West Riding, England":"Yorkshire West Riding, Inglismaa, U